   "source": [
    "# Lab 2 — Regression (California Housing) — SOLUTION\n",
    "\n",
    "**Objective:** Predict median house value for California census block groups.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Dataset:** California Housing — 20,640 samples, 8 features, target = median house value (100,000 USD)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 1: Imports and load data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.datasets import fetch_california_housing\n",
    "from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n",
    "from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error\n",
    "\n",
    "data = fetch_california_housing()\n",
    "X = data.data\n",
    "y = data.target\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"X shape:\", X.shape)\n",
    "print(\"y shape:\", y.shape)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 2: Train–test split"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Train size:\", len(y_train))\n",
    "print(\"Test size:\", len(y_test))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 3: Train the model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "model = LinearRegression()\n",
    "model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
    "pred = model.predict(X_test)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Step 4: Evaluate"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print(mean_squared_error(y_test, pred))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Optional: Feature coefficients (for Lab Q2)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "for name, coef in zip(data.feature_names, model.coef_):\n",
    "    print(f\"{name}: {coef:.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Intercept: {model.intercept_:.4f}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Lab questions — Sample answers\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Interpret the MSE.** MSE is the average squared prediction error. Typical values on this dataset are around 0.5–0.6. Since y is in units of 100,000 USD, RMSE ≈ 0.7 means roughly \$70,000 average error in price. \"Good\" or \"bad\" depends on context; lower is better.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **What features influence price most?** MedInc (median income) usually has the largest positive coefficient — higher income is associated with higher predicted price. Latitude/Longitude can be negative (e.g. moving north). Use the printed coefficients above to list and interpret."
   ]
  }
